Javier’s daughter, Jacklyn Cazares was killed in the Uvalde school shooting. Both survivors and family members impacted by gun violence were in attendance including people connected with the Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting. December 14th marks the tenth anniversary of the shooting.
(Photos by @mattmcclainphoto /The Washington Post) #photojournalism #washingtondc

4. Aliyana Stokes, 10, and her brother, Bryson Stokes, 5, right, take part in a gun safety class for children with plastic replica guns as people gather at Choppa Community gun range on Sunday July 10, 2022 in Welcome, MD.

Wanted to share the edit of my Choppa Community gun range story. Honored to have had it place in Picture of the Year International and NPPA Best of Photojournalism in the Feature Picture Story category. Thanks to @nataliajimenez for the edit.
Choppa Community gun range has become a place for African American gun owners and others to assemble to learn gun safety, self-defense and have a place to target practice. Many are from nearby Washington, DC and Baltimore, MD and have been affected by gun violence. The rates of gun related crimes in large metropolitan cities across the United States has been on the rise. This has caused many people to obtain guns as a means of personal protection. (Photos by @mattmcclainphoto /The Washington Post) #photojournalisms

2. The setting sun in reflected in the window of the home of Jack Clark and his wife, Rachel Clark is seen at the Jimmy Carter Boyhood Farm on Wednesday February 22, 2023 in Plains, GA.The family was influential to former President Jimmy Carter as he was raised on the farm. Jack helped run the farm for Carter’s father, James Earl Carter Sr. 
3. A mule is seen out the kitchen window at the home of Jack Clark and his wife, Rachel Clark is seen at the Jimmy Carter Boyhood Farm.
4. National Park Service employee, Ronald Hobkirk works on a bell at the Jimmy Carter Boyhood Farm on Wednesday February 22, 2023 in Plains, GA.

6. Items are seen in the gift shop of the Jimmy Carter National Historical Park Visitor Center, which is housed in the former Plains High School on Friday February 24, 2023 in Plains, GA. 
#jimmycarter #georgia

Tomorrow, April 1st marks my tenth anniversary as a staff photojournalist at The Washington Post. Technically I started as a contract photographer at the end of 2010, but was hired on staff in 2013. Here is a random selection of photos from over the years. (Photos by @mattmcclainphoto /The Washington Post) 
1. Zach Cardwell, right, watches the Flying Heels Rodeo as a rainbow streaks across the sky as a storm passes through on Saturday July 03, 2021 in Granby, CO.
2. Workers adjust flags before a Hillary Clinton election night event at the Javits Center on Tuesday November 8, 2016 in New York City, New York.
3. People are reflected in mirrors along a staircase at a business on Venice Beach on Monday August 16, 2021 in Venice, CA.
4. Erin Herrgott, 20, of Oxford, MI, center, is talked to by instructor, Howard Parsons after arriving with other new trainees at the United States Border Patrol Academy on Wednesday August 29, 2018 in Artesia, NM. 
5. Christian Jacobs, 7, sits against the headstone of his father, U.S. Marine Corps Sgt. Christopher James Jacobs as he visits in observance of Memorial Day at Arlington National Cemetery on Monday May 28, 2018 in Arlington, VA. Christopher died during a training exercise in 2011.
6. People cross a bridge on Sunday May 03, 2015 in the Nuwakot District of Nepal following a deadly earthquake.
7. Ivan Leyva picks tobacco in a field on Friday August 30, 2013 in Warfield, VA.
8. Rodeo participants warm up horses as the setting sun illuminates dust during an evening rodeo that was part of Pioneer Days on Saturday May 05, 2018 in Guymon, OK. 
9. President-elect, Donald Trump poses for a portrait at Trump Tower on Tuesday January 17, 2017 in New York, NY. 
10. Pamela Weems of Minneapolis, MN poses next to a man with a sign protesting against President Donald Trump near the White House as security personnel are seen on the roof on Wednesday August 26, 2020 in Washington, DC.

Preston Malvoisin, 7, is a regular competitor at the Rafter K Rodeo in King, NC where he rides calves. Preston's mother, Amanda Paquette has decided to continue to have her son compete because he enjoys it and also seeing the rodeo community as having positive male role models for Preston. Look for the story at www.washingtonpost.com. (Photos by @mattmcclainphoto /The Washington Post)

Scenes from Streetbeefs events on July 1st and August 5th, 2023 in Winchester, VA that were part of my essay on rural Virginia that was part of "A Capitol Summer" project published today at www.washingtonpost.com. In order to keep disputes from causing violence in the community, Chris Wilmore started Streetbeefs. The monthly fighting events, that meet in a homeowners country field in Virginia, give people the chance to settle their problems in the ring with boxing, mixed martial arts and kick boxing. There are also matches that don't involve a grudge. Streetbeefs continues to grow with a large social media presence and has also become a platform for young and up and coming fighters looking to make a name for themselves. 
(Photos by @mattmcclainphoto /The Washington Post) #photojournalism #virginia #boxing
